{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566260"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:38:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:38:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18778"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18778"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.08,0.49,0.29,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11511"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77557"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11511"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18778"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63070"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1845"},{"type":"tags","id":"2132"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2915"},{"type":"tags","id":"2942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"6429"},{"type":"tags","id":"11539"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26643"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43704"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77557"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of fatigue, joint pain, and frothy urine. She has noticed her ankles are swollen and her urine appears dark. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. She has bilateral pitting ankle oedema. Urinalysis shows 3+ blood, 2+ protein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine 250 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003Cbr /\u003EUrea 15.0 mmol/L (2.5-7.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EHaemoglobin 98 g/L (115-155)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amyloidosis","Thin basement membrane disease","ANCA-associated vasculitis","Membranous nephropathy","Minimal change disease"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of nephritic syndrome (haematuria, proteinuria, hypertension, and reduced renal function) along with systemic symptoms including fatigue, joint pain, and fever. The acute presentation with multi-system involvement strongly suggests a vasculitic process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EANCA-associated vasculitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with constitutional symptoms (fatigue, fever, weight loss), musculoskeletal involvement (arthralgia, myalgia), and renal involvement (rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis). The combination of active urinary sediment, reduced renal function, and systemic symptoms makes this the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmyloidosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with nephrotic syndrome (heavy proteinuria, hypoalbuminaemia, oedema) rather than nephritic syndrome. While it can affect multiple organs, it usually has a more indolent course and rarely presents with active inflammation or joint pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThin basement membrane disease\u003C/strong\u003E is typically benign, presenting with isolated microscopic haematuria. It does not cause systemic symptoms or significant proteinuria. It rarely causes reduced renal function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMembranous nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E characteristically presents with nephrotic syndrome. While it can have an associated systemic disease, it typically does not present with significant haematuria or systemic inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMinimal change disease\u003C/strong\u003E presents with pure nephrotic syndrome, typically without haematuria or reduced renal function. It is more common in children and young adults, and rarely associated with systemic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nephritic syndrome is characterised by haematuria, proteinuria, hypertension, and renal impairment."],"references":["Hashmi MS, Pandey J. Nephritic Syndrome. In: StatPearls [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK562240/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63070"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18778"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63070"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T13:59:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T14:00:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11511"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77557"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading"